    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "IX-7MnFhVNoT"
      },
      "source": [
        "As you can see, the prompt comes back with a tonne of information that we can use when we're building our applications!\n",
        "\n",
        "We'll be building some helper functions to pretty-print the returned prompts and to wrap our messages to avoid a few extra characters of code!"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "IB76LJrDVgbc"
      },
      "source": [
        "##### Helper Functions"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 7,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "-vmtUV7WVOLW"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "from IPython.display import display, Markdown\n",
        "\n",
        "def get_response(client: OpenAI, messages: str, model: str = \"gpt-4.1-nano\") -> str:\n",
        "    return client.chat.completions.create(\n",
        "        model=model,\n",
        "        messages=messages\n",
        "    )\n",
        "\n",
        "def system_prompt(message: str) -> dict:\n",
        "    return {\"role\": \"developer\", \"content\": message}\n",
        "\n",
        "def assistant_prompt(message: str) -> dict:\n",
        "    return {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": message}\n",
        "\n",
        "def user_prompt(message: str) -> dict:\n",
        "    return {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": message}\n",
        "\n",
        "def pretty_print(message: str) -> str:\n",
        "    display(Markdown(message.choices[0].message.content))"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "osXgB_5nVky_"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Testing Helper Functions\n",
        "\n",
        "Now we can leverage OpenAI's endpoints with a bit less boiler plate - let's rewrite our original prompt with these helper functions!\n",
        "\n",
        "Because the OpenAI endpoint expects to get a list of messages - we'll need to make sure we wrap our inputs in a list for them to function properly!"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 8,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 237
        },
        "id": "4yRwAWvgWFNq",
        "outputId": "777e7dcb-43e3-491a-d94a-f543e19b61e6"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": [
              "LangChain and LlamaIndex (formerly known as GPT Index) are both popular frameworks designed to facilitate the development of applications leveraging large language models (LLMs). While they share similar goals in enabling more effective application development with LLMs, they have distinct focuses and features. Here's a comparison to clarify their differences:\n",
              "\n",
              "**1. Purpose and Focus**\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LangChain:**\n",
              "  - **Primary Focus:** Building composable, multi-step, conversational applications with LLMs.\n",
              "  - **Core Capabilities:** Chain-based architecture that allows developers to assemble complex workflows, including prompts, memory, agents, and tools.\n",
              "  - **Use Cases:** Chatbots, question-answering systems, virtual assistants, and more complex AI workflows.\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LlamaIndex (GPT Index):**\n",
              "  - **Primary Focus:** Efficiently ingesting, indexing, and querying large external data sources (documents, PDFs, databases) using LLMs.\n",
              "  - **Core Capabilities:** Building data indices that facilitate fast retrieval and question-answering over vast or complex document collections.\n",
              "  - **Use Cases:** Document search, knowledge bases, content summarization, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).\n",
              "\n",
              "**2. Core Components**\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LangChain:**\n",
              "  - Chains: Sequential prompts and processing steps.\n",
              "  - Agents: Dynamic decision-making systems that determine which tools and chains to invoke.\n",
              "  - Memory: Persistent context across interactions.\n",
              "  - Integrations: Supports numerous LLM providers and other tools.\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LlamaIndex:**\n",
              "  - Data Connectors: Ingest data from various sources (files, APIs, databases).\n",
              "  - Indices: Structures like trees, graphs, or simple lists for organizing data.\n",
              "  - Query Engines: Facilitate retrieval-based interactions with the indexed data.\n",
              "  - Embedding & Storage: Manages embeddings, vector databases, and filtering for efficient retrieval.\n",
              "\n",
              "**3. Usage Paradigm**\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LangChain:** Designed for building sophisticated workflows that combine multiple components—prompt templates, language models, external tools, and memory—to create advanced conversational AI applications.\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LlamaIndex:** Focused on creating indices over raw data to enable efficient retrieval and question-answering, especially for applications that require search over large document collections.\n",
              "\n",
              "**4. Integration with LLMs**\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LangChain:** Provides a broad abstraction over multiple LLM providers (OpenAI, Hugging Face, Anthropic, etc.) and includes tools for prompt management, chaining, and reasoning.\n",
              "\n",
              "- **LlamaIndex:** Primarily used for document-based retrieval tasks, leveraging LLMs for answering questions using the indexed data. It often works alongside embeddings and vector stores.\n",
              "\n",
              "---\n",
              "\n",
              "**Summary:**\n",
              "\n",
              "| Aspect                     | LangChain                                        | LlamaIndex (GPT Index)                                    |\n",
              "|----------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------|\n",
              "| Main Goal                  | Building complex AI workflows and chatbots     | Indexing and querying large external data sources        |\n",
              "| Focus Area                 | Workflow orchestration, chaining, agents        | Data ingestion, indexing, retrieval, and Q&A             |\n",
              "| Typical Use Cases          | Conversational agents, multi-step reasoning    | Document search, knowledge bases, retrieval-based Q&A  |\n",
              "| Data Handling              | Less focused on raw data indexing                | Specialized in data ingestion and search                 |\n",
              "\n",
              "**In summary:**  \n",
              "- Use **LangChain** if you want to build sophisticated interactive applications, conversational agents, or complex workflows involving multiple steps and tools.  \n",
              "- Use **LlamaIndex** if your primary need is to ingest, index, and retrieve information from large data collections to enable precise question-answering or search functionalities.\n",
              "\n",
              "---\n",
              "\n",
              "If you're building an AI assistant that needs to process and understand large document datasets, LlamaIndex is often the go-to. If you're designing multi-step reasoning, conversational dialogue, or integrating various tools and APIs, LangChain offers more robust workflow capabilities."
            ],
            "text/plain": [
              "<IPython.core.display.Markdown object>"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "output_type": "display_data"
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "messages = [user_prompt(YOUR_PROMPT)]\n",
        "\n",
        "chatgpt_response = get_response(client, messages)\n",
        "\n",
        "pretty_print(chatgpt_response)"
      ]
    },
